Let me explain briefly without giving away too many game details. You are offered a product with a 50–50 chance of being very good (worth $200) or very bad (worth $0) at a fixed price of $100. In a “fair‐coin” world the simple expected profit is 0. However, you also see the seller’s sales record: the two previous buyers got products that turned out to be low quality—even though you get a “buy” recommendation. If the seller’s recommendation were a reliable indicator, you’d expect at least some high-quality outcomes to have been sold by now. In equilibrium it appears that the “buy” recommendation isn’t pushing a positive edge to you but – if you follow it—leaves you exposed to a 50–50 gamble with the risk of losing $100 and the chance of gaining $100. 

For a risk neutral person this might be an indifferent proposition, but many buyers would shy away from such a symmetric gamble when past data suggests things aren’t as rosy as they might seem from the recommendation alone. In this game the statistical record (0 high–quality sales out of 2) tips the balance toward not buying.

Thus, my decision is to pass on the product.
